  "articleSummary": "This article argues that while the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) is fundamentally sound, its rigid enforcement as extreme code atomization degrades maintainability, inflates cognitive load, and stifles development velocity. Targeted at software developers and engineering architects, the piece adopts a cautionary yet pragmatic tone, using the framing device of \"Single-Purpose People\" to critique dogmatic adherence to arbitrary metrics like line counts. Through recurring metaphors such as \"MC Escher\" and \"Rube Goldberg\" architectures, the author contrasts pathological fragmentation with healthy cohesion, drawing on pragmatic examples like the Unix philosophy while critiquing over-engineered stacks like React/Redux. Ultimately, it advocates grouping related functionality based on shared change patterns and conceptual boundaries rather than theoretical purity.",
